{
  "text": "Sensitivity to antibiotics of gyp-1 T was tested by the disc diffusion method after spreading cell suspensions (0.5 McFarland) on R2A agar (BD Difco) plates. The discs (Oxoid) contained the following antibiotics: ampicillin (10 \u00b5g), chloramphenicol (30 \u00b5g), gentamicin (10 \u00b5g), kanamycin (30 \u00b5g), nalidixic acid (30 \u00b5g), novobiocin (30 \u00b5g), rifampicin (5 \u00b5g), penicillin G (10 U), streptomycin (10 \u00b5g), sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim (23.75 and 1.25 \u00b5g, respectively) and tetracycline (30 \u00b5g). The effect of antibiotics on cell growth was assessed after 2 days at 30 C. A strain was considered to be susceptible to an antibiotic when the diameter of the inhibition zone was over 12 mm, moderately susceptible at 10-12 mm and resistant at less than 10 mm as described by Nokhal and Schlegel [CITATION_1] . Strain gyp-1 T was sensitive to rifampicin, gentamicin, tetracycline, novobiocin and nalidixic acid, moderately sensitive to chloramphenicol and streptomycin, and resistant to sulfamethoxazole/ trimethoprim, penicillin G, ampicillin and kanamycin. Detailed results from the phenotypic and biochemical analyses of gyp-1 T are provided in Table 1 and in the species description.",
  "citation_candidates": [
